    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                    <p>
                      <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>6A</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/> <citedRange>6A</citedRange> </bibl> [last consulted 03/07/2026]).</p>
                <p>
                      Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2007d"/>, <citedRange>303 nn. 65, 68</citedRange> (on <foreign xml:lang="grc">πεπαμένος</foreign>)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#CrespoGiannakis2019"/>, <citedRange>41</citedRange> (on dialect mixture)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Crosby2022"/>, <citedRange>84 n. 64</citedRange> (on the use of the optative)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2024"/>, <citedRange>§7</citedRange> (on <foreign xml:lang="grc">πεπαμένος</foreign>)</bibl>.
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                       <ab>
   <lb n="1"/>ἐ͂ πέπατα<supplied reason="omitted">ι</supplied> καὶ πεπαμέ<lb n="2" break="no"/>νος λϊόν κα πράσοι; 
</ab>
</div>
            <div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
                <app loc="l. 1"><rdg>ΠΕΠΑΤΑ</rdg> <note>on the lamella</note></app>
                <app loc="l. 2"><note>i.e.</note> <rdg>πράσ<supplied reason="omitted">σ</supplied>οι</rdg></app>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Has he acquired it, and would he fare better for having acquired it?</p>
                </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
                <p>¿Lo ha adquirido y le iría mejor habiéndolo adquirido?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>On the productive lexical family of <foreign xml:lang="grc">πάομαι</foreign> (Att.-Ion. <foreign xml:lang="grc">κτάομαι</foreign>) in the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2007"/>, <citedRange>302-304</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2024"/>, <citedRange>§4.1</citedRange></bibl>. For misspellings in the oracular lamellae, see <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2018b"/>, <citedRange>267-272</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                
                 <p n="Ithaca results">Ithaca attributes the inscription to Epirus with a confidence of 94.23% and dates it most probably to the beginning of the fourth century BC, with a peak probability for 400-390 BC. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline6A_2026_06_24.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline6A.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline6A_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
        </body>
